Tobacco smoke and risk of bacterial infection. Tobacco smoke is a proven risk factor for bacterial infection.In adults without COPD, smoking is associated with a significant increase in the relative risk (RR) of pneumonia (RR=2.97 95% CI 1.52-5.81), S pneumoniae pneumonia (RR=2.50Exposure to tobacco smoke approximately doubles the risk of infection. This increased burden of infection has significant healthcare cost implications. Each infectious episode in an individual should prompt an attempt at smoking cessation.